 teacher who offers analysis rather than polemic to explain why today's teachers and scholars are at once breaking new ground and treading familiar paths. It opens the door to an important nationwide and worldwide conversation about the reorganization of knowledge and the categories in and through which we teach the humanities. And it does so in a spirit both generous and optimistic about the present and the future of these disciplines.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh  aAdjective.  aAestheticism.  aAlan Sokal.  aAlfred Kazin.  aAmateur professionalism.  aAmateur.  aAmerican studies.  aAnti-intellectualism.  aAphorism.  aArt history.  aAuthor.  aBook review.  aC. P. Snow.  aC. S. Lewis.  aColumnist.  aCounterintuitive.  aCritical theory.  aCriticism.  aCultural studies.  aCulture war.  aDeconstruction.  aDoublespeak.  aEdward Said.  aEssay.  aFashionable Nonsense.  aGenre.  aGeorge Orwell.  aGertrude Stein.  aHarvard University.  aHeadline.  aHumanities.  aIdealization.  aIdeology.  aIntellectual.  aInterdisciplinarity.  aIrony.  aJacques Derrida.  aJacques Lacan.  aJames Gleick.  aJargon.  aJewish studies.  aJonathan Swift.  aJoseph Addison.  aJudith Butler.  aLiberal arts education.  aLiterary criticism.  aLiterary theory.  aLiterature.  aMario Pei.  aMinima Moralia.  aModern Language Association.  aMr.  aNeologism.  aNew Criticism.  aNewspeak.  aNovelist.  aOxford University Press.  aPenis envy.  aPhilosopher.  aPhilosophy.  aPhrase.  aPhysicist.  aPoetry.  aPolitical correctness.  aPolitician.  aPost-structuralism.  aPostmodernism.  aPrince Hal.  aPsychoanalysis.  aPsychology.  aRhetoric.  aRichard Feynman.  aRobert Maynard 